    description: 'Built in just fifteen months on Ocarina of Time\'s engine and recycled character models, Majora\'s Mask took the safest possible starting point and produced the strangest, darkest, most structurally radical game Nintendo has ever made.',
    longDescription: 'Majora\'s Mask exists because of a constraint. Eiji Aonuma, who had led dungeon design on Ocarina of Time, was unenthusiastic about simply redesigning those dungeons for a planned expansion, so Shigeru Miyamoto challenged the team to build an entirely new game using the existing engine and graphics — in one year. Working with a smaller team, they delivered in fifteen months, reusing Ocarina\'s character models and assets wholesale. Every incentive pointed toward a safe, familiar retread. Instead they produced the most experimental game in the series.\n\nThe central innovation is the three-day cycle. Link arrives in the parallel world of Termina to find the moon — a vast, leering, grotesque face — falling toward the land, due to strike in three days. When the seventy-two hours run out, the world ends, and Link must play the Song of Time to return to the first morning, undoing everything he has accomplished except the most permanent achievements. The player is placed in a perpetual loop, forced to plan across a compressed timetable, learn the movements and routines of every townsperson, and repeat sections with hard-won knowledge. It is a structure closer to a puzzle box than a traditional adventure, and nothing in Zelda before or since has resembled it.\n\nThe reused character models became an unexpected creative asset rather than a liability. Aonuma has reflected that the decision was partly practical and partly stylistic — that familiar faces from Ocarina, transplanted into Termina, could express something they never could in their original setting. Seeing recognisable characters living out doomed final days, trapped in loops of grief, denial, and unfinished business, gave the game an uncanny, haunted quality. The masks that transform Link into other beings deepen the theme, since each is created from the regrets of the dead.\n\nThe result is a Zelda game about mortality, loss, and the impossibility of saving everyone — tonally unlike anything Nintendo has published before or after. Its darkness and structural difficulty made it divisive at release, but its reputation has grown enormously, and it is now widely regarded as among the most artistically ambitious games the company has ever produced. That such a strange, uncompromising work emerged from a mandate to reuse old assets on a compressed schedule remains one of the great creative paradoxes in gaming.',
