    description: 'Hideo Kojima marketed a sequel starring Solid Snake, then swapped him out for an unknown rookie after the prologue — a deliberate betrayal of the player that made MGS2 the first genuinely postmodern video game.',
    longDescription: 'Metal Gear Solid 2 is built on an act of calculated deception aimed squarely at its own audience. Every trailer, every trade-show demo, every scrap of marketing showed Solid Snake and the Tanker chapter, and Kojima ensured that nothing revealed what came next. Players bought the game expecting to control the hero of the original. They played the Tanker prologue as Snake — and then the game moved to the Big Shell and handed them Raiden, a slim, untested, unfamiliar rookie who was emphatically not the man they had come for.\n\nThe swap was not a twist for its own sake. Kojima has explained that he was uncomfortable with the idea of a killer like Snake being idolised as a hero, and he wanted to force players to re-examine that admiration by denying them the fantasy. Raiden functions as a surrogate for the player: a fan of Snake\'s legend, trained entirely in simulations, following orders from voices he cannot verify, being manoeuvred through a scenario designed to make him into a copy of a man he has only heard stories about. The player\'s frustration at not being Snake is the point, and the game weaponises it.\n\nFrom that foundation Kojima constructed what has often been called the first postmodern video game. He stated that a postmodern plot was one of his central goals, and the game delivers it: the Patriots, an AI system controlling society, reveal that the entire Big Shell mission was the S3 Plan — "Selection for Societal Sanity" — an artificial scenario built to shape Raiden by replicating the events of the first game. The AI then lectures the player directly on information overload, the manufacture of context, memetic inheritance, and the curation of truth in a digital age, in a monologue that broke the fourth wall and unsettled everyone who reached it. The game turns on the player, on sequels, and on the medium itself.\n\nReleased in 2001, MGS2 was received with bafflement and anger by many players who felt cheated of the Snake game they had been sold. Two decades later its reputation is transformed: its warnings about algorithmic curation of reality and the erosion of shared truth read as uncannily prophetic, and it is widely regarded as a landmark that questioned what a video game sequel could be. It remains the definitive example of a blockbuster deliberately sabotaging its own audience\'s expectations in service of an argument.',
